{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491316"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"910"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/910"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.02,0.05,0.52,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48326"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/910"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"361"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35124"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48326"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of left calf pain, which occurs after walking 50 metres and is relieved by rest. He has not seen a doctor for a number of years and takes no regular medications. He has a 40-pack-year smoking history and works as a bus driver. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 138/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The left femoral pulse is reduced in volume and the distal pulses of the left leg are not palpable. The ankle-brachial index (ABI) is 0.8 (0.91-1.31) on the right and 0.4 (0.91-1.31) on the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Angiography","Toe pressures","Apixaban","Arterial duplex studies","Aspirin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe finding of an ankle-brachial index of 0.4 in the left leg confirms the clinical diagnosis of intermittent claudication and significant peripheral arterial disease. With this finding and the severity of his symptoms, further investigation is warranted and this should start with \u003Cstrong\u003Earterial duplex flow studies\u003C/strong\u003E from aorta to left ankle. This non-invasive imaging modality can provide detailed information about the location and extent of arterial disease, which is crucial for planning further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConventional \u003Cstrong\u003Eangiography\u003C/strong\u003E would be the next step if and when the patient was considered for a revascularisation procedure. It is more invasive and carries risks such as contrast-induced nephropathy and arterial injury, so it is not the most appropriate first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToe pressures\u003C/strong\u003E are useful in patients with calcified, incompressible arteries where ABI may be falsely elevated. However, in this case, we already have a diagnostic ABI result, so toe pressures would not provide additional useful information at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is an oral anticoagulant and would not be indicated in the routine management of peripheral arterial disease. It is primarily used for conditions such as atrial fibrillation or venous thromboembolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of the long-term management of peripheral arterial disease to reduce cardiovascular risk. However, it is not the most appropriate next step at this point. Further investigation of the extent and location of the arterial disease is needed before initiating treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Diagnosis of peripheral arterial disease begins with simple non-invasive ankle-brachial index and a doppler flow studies.","Arterial duplex studies are the next appropriate step after an abnormal ankle-brachial index in the investigation of peripheral arterial disease."],"references":["Kullo IJ, Rooke TW. Peripheral Artery Disease. N Engl J Med 2016; 374:861-71. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26962905/","Kohlman-Trigoboff D. Update: Diagnosis and Management of Peripheral Arterial Disease. J Nurse Pract. 2019;15(1):87-95.e1. Available at: https://www.npjournal.org/article/S1555-4155(18)30645-7/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"910"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33244"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-10T05:27:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T09:25:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"910"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48326"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCo